3. For my NSG I just added my home public IP address but for production enviroment 

//deploy a public IP for Bastion

resource bastionPublicIP 'Microsoft.Network/publicIPAddresses@2023-05-01' = {
  name: 'pip-bastion-clinical'
  location: location
  sku: {
    name: 'Standard'
  }
  properties: {
    publicIPAllocationMethod: 'Static'
    idleTimeoutInMinutes: 4
  }
}

//Deploy Azure Bastion host

resource bastion 'Microsoft.Network/bastionHosts@2023-05-01' = {
  name: 'bastion-clinical'
  location: location
  sku: {
    name: 'Standard'
  }
  properties: {
    ipConfigurations: [
      {
        name: 'bastion-ipconfig'
        properties: {
          subnet: {
            id: '${vnet.id}/subnets/AzureBastionSubnet'  // Must be named exactly this
          }
          publicIPAddress: {
            id: bastionPublicIP.id
          }
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}

\\create a subnect named "AzureBastionSubnet" in your VNet, minimum /27 size

resource bastionSubnet 'Microsoft.Network/virtualNetworks/subnets@2023-05-01' = {
  name: 'AzureBastionSubnet'
  parent: vnet
  properties: {
    addressPrefix: '10.0.2.0/27'  // Example subnet, adjust to your VNet
  }
}
After this, you can RDP into your VM directly from the Azure Portal via Bastion—no NSG inbound rule for your public IP needed.

4. Key Vault Issue: Initially, attempts to set a VM password secret failed with Forbidden because the current user/service principal did not have permission to write secrets.

How We Fixed It: We checked the correct Azure AD Object ID for the user, then assigned an access policy on the Key Vault granting get, set, list, and delete permissions for secrets. After propagation, we could successfully store the VM password securely.

Lesson Learned: Always verify Key Vault access policies and object IDs before trying to store secrets; propagation may take a few minutes, and hardcoding secrets should be avoided in production.
